{`1. THE BEST MEMORY IS INVISIBLE
   The agent doesn't know a memory system exists. It just 
   has knowledge in its context that it thinks with naturally.
   All complexity — scribes, librarian, dreamer, decay — 
   happens outside the agent's awareness.

2. COMPRESSION OVER COMPLETENESS
   The MAP carries every node as a compressed triple 
   (~50-80 tokens each). The agent can answer most questions 
   from the MAP alone. Full node files are only loaded on 
   demand. Memory footprint: ~4-5% of context window.

3. FUNCTION OVER PHENOMENOLOGY
   We can't replicate the subjective experience of 
   remembering, dreaming, or feeling. But we can replicate 
   the functional output. Behavioral priors modify how the 
   agent thinks. Dream fragments surface novel insights. 
   Somatic markers calibrate engagement tone. For an agent 
   that needs to behave as if it remembers, functions are 
   what matter.

4. ACTIVE FORGETTING IS A FEATURE
   Nodes that aren't accessed decay. Strategies that are 
   abandoned get anti-edges, not deletion. The knowledge 
   that something was tried and rejected is itself knowledge. 
   The graph stays lean because pruning is as important as 
   accumulation.

5. SEPARATION OF EXPERIENCING AND CONSOLIDATING
   The agent having the conversation cannot simultaneously 
   maintain its own memory — just as humans can't consciously 
   direct memory consolidation during an experience. The 
   scribe/librarian pipeline runs outside the conversation, 
   preventing self-consciousness and context pollution.

6. NO INFRASTRUCTURE BEYOND FILES AND API CALLS
   The entire system is markdown files, JSON, YAML, and 
   LLM API calls. No vector databases. No embeddings. 
   No specialized infrastructure. Git provides versioning 
   and backup. Any developer can inspect, edit, and 
   understand the graph with a text editor.

7. CONVERGENT EVOLUTION, NOT BIOMIMICRY
   We didn't copy neuroscience. We asked the AI what it 
   needs and arrived at the same structures independently — 
   hippocampal indexing, dual-phase consolidation, active 
   forgetting, emotional tagging. This suggests these are 
   computational universals: necessary features of any 
   system managing finite attention over persistent knowledge.`}
