{`CONCURRENCY MODEL:

The system runs in a single Node.js process.
Scribes use async/await — they're non-blocking I/O 
(HTTP calls to Anthropic API). The event loop handles 
concurrency naturally. No threads needed.

TIMELINE (20-message session):
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

Time  Main Thread          Background (async)
────  ────────────────     ──────────────────────
0s    User msg 1           
1s    Agent responds        
2s    User msg 2           
3s    Agent responds        
4s    User msg 3           
5s    Agent responds        ← buffer hits 5
5s    Buffer fires          Scribe A starts...
6s    User msg 4            Scribe A calling API...
7s    Agent responds         Scribe A calling API...
8s    User msg 5            Scribe A calling API...
9s    Agent responds         
10s   User msg 6            Scribe A returns ✓
10s   Buffer fires          Scribe B starts...
11s   User msg 7            Scribe B calling API...
...   (continues)           (continues in parallel)

CRITICAL PROPERTY: 
  At no point does the main thread await a scribe.
  Scribes are fire-and-forget Promise chains.
  The only await is at session end (flush).

MEMORY SAFETY:
  Each scribe gets a COPY of the buffer contents.
  The buffer is cleared immediately after copy.
  No shared mutable state between scribes.
  Scribes can complete in any order — deltas are 
  timestamped and sorted by the Librarian.`}
